25|$|Peerages {{were largely}} {{hereditary}} until the regular creation of <b>life</b> <b>peers</b> {{began in the}} second half of the 20th century. The last creation of a non-royal hereditary peer occurred in 1984; even then it was considered unusual. <b>Life</b> <b>peers</b> and 92 hereditary peers still retain the right to sit and vote in the House of Lords, though their power is restricted and further reform of the House of Lords is under consideration.|$|R
